                                Report abuseTranscript of Jonathan Edwards and Cotton MatherJonathan Edwards and Cotton MatherCotton Mather'S early lifeCOTTON MATHER (1662-1727). He was the eldest son of New England's leading divine, Increase Mather, and grandson of the colony's spiritual founders Richaard Mather and John Cotton. Mather was born in Boston, educated at Harvard and received an honorary Doctor of Divinity degree from Glasgow University.Jonathan Edwards Early lifeJonathan, the only son, was the fifth of 11 children. He was trained for college by his father and elder sisters, all  had a great education, Esther, the eldest, wrote a semi-humorous tract on the immateriality of the soul, often mistakenly attributed to Jonathan.Why we careMather's interest in the craft and actions of Satan that won him an audience with the most powerful figures involved in the trial proceedings, several of the judges and the local ministers in Salem.Johnathan Edwards born after trials helped in developing new era.ViewsBoth wanted everyone to be religous and to accept god. He also wanted people to get rid of demonsOtherCotton said he was visited by an angel at age 30 and both wrote and published many works.Common themesSome common themes through out their books include religion, being good, and what happens to sinners.QuestionsHow many sisters did Jonathan have?T/F both were religious.T/F both wrote and published works.T/F Cotton was the eldest son.T/F Cotton didn't beleive in god.Answers10TTTFFull transcriptMore presentations by
    
        
